,"type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Waddon in Portisham (Dorset). Some of the bearers cited here may belong to (2) below. There may have been some confusion with   Whaddon  .","2  English: locative name from Waddon in Croydon (Surrey)."],"variants":[{"name":"Whaddon","meanings":["English: locative name from any of the various places called Whaddon (Bucks, Cambs, Gloucs, Wilts). There may have been some confusion with   Waddon  ."]},{"name":"Wadding","meanings":["English (Hampshire, Isle of Wight and Gloucestershire): variant of <b>Waddon</b>, a habitational name from either Waddon in Portisham (Dorset) or from Waddon in Croydon (Surrey). Both names derive from Old English <i>wād</i> ‘woad’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Elizabeth Waddon was born in 1300, in Waddon, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, her father, Lord Ralph Waddon, was 20 and her mother, Mrs. Ralph Waddon, was 17. She married Sir. John Hedworth Baron in 1330, in Sunderland, Durham, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1330, in her hometown, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1300–1330":"1300–1330","1330–1363":"1330–1363","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1283–Female":"1283–Surnud","1300":"1300","1330":"1330","1363":"1363","1283":"1283","1280":"1280","Waddon, Croydon, Surrey, England":"Waddon, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Weymouth, Dorset, England":"Weymouth, Dorset, England","Sunderland, Durham, England":"Sunderland, Durham, England"},"fi":{"1300–1330":"1300–1330","1330–1363":"1330–1363","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1283–Female":"1283–Kuollut","1300":"1300","1330":"1330","1363":"1363","1283":"1283","1280":"1280","Waddon, Croydon, Surrey, England":"Waddon, Surrey, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Weymouth, Dorset, England":"Weymouth, Dorset, England","Sunderland, Durham, England":"Sunderland, Durham, England"},"fr":{"1300–1330":"1300–1330","1330–1363":"1330–1363","1280–Male":"1280–Décédé","1283–Female":"1283–Décédée","1300":"1300","1330":"1330","1363":"1363","1283":"1283","1280":"1280","Waddon, Croydon, Surrey, England":"Waddon, Surrey, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Weymouth, Dorset, England":"Weymouth, Dorset, Angleterre","Sunderland, Durham, England":"Sunderland, Durham, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Lady Elizabeth Waddon est née en 1300, à Waddon, Surrey, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Lord Ralph Waddon, avait 20 ans et sa mère, Mrs. Ralph Waddon, avait 17 ans. Elle a épousé Sir. John Hedworth Baron en 1330, à Sunderland, Durham, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée en 1330, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 30 ans."},"de":{"1300–1330":"1300–1330","1330–1363":"1330–1363","12